~~~~~~~~~2.WM-STARTUP~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
1. Make sure you have xorg-xinit installed (because we need to install
   in order to have our '.xinitrc' file working, and to able to start our
   graphical environment with the "startx" command).

2. Asuming you haven't installed any other shell, you should have a
   '.bash_profile' file in your home folder. We are going to add an 'IF'
   statement, that automatically starts X if no other graphical server
   is loaded:
        \ IN .bash_profile ADD: /
         =======================
```bash
# Automatically start X (via startx) when logging into tty1, but only if no X session is running
# - The first condition checks if the DISPLAY variable is unset, meaning no graphical session is active.
# - The second condition ensures this only happens on tty1 (XDG_VTNR = 1), so it doesn't interfere with other terminals.
if [ -z "${DISPLAY}" ] && [ "${XDG_VTNR}" -eq 1 ]; then
    exec startx
fi
```

3. We need to create our '.xinitrc' file in our home folder, and paste
   this content with the explanations:
        \ IN .xinitrc ADD: /
         ==================
```bash
# .xinitrc - Configuration file for starting X sessions with `startx`
# This file is executed by `startx` when starting an X session.

# ---- SCREEN LAYOUT (OPTIONAL) ----
# If you want to set a specific screen resolution or layout, you can use `xrandr`.
# Example: Set your screen resolution to 1920x1080. You can adjust this based on your monitor setup.
# This is especially useful for high-resolution displays (e.g., 4K), where you might need scaling.
# You can check available resolutions with the command: xrandr

# Basic syntax:
# xrandr --output <output-device> --mode <resolution> --scale <scaling-factor>

# xrandr --output <your-output-device> --mode <resolution>
# xrandr --output HDMI-1 --mode 1920x1080

# To find available display resolutions and output names, run `xrandr` in your terminal.

# Example:
# Run `xrandr` and you'll see something like:
# HDMI-1 connected primary 3840x2160+0+0 (normal left inverted right x axis y axis) 598mm x 336mm
# This means your output device is HDMI-1 and your screen resolution is 3840x2160 (4K).

# ---- SCREEN SCALING (ZOOM) ----
# On 4K monitors (3840x2160), you may want to scale things up for readability.
# Here's how scaling works for different zoom levels:

# 1x Scaling (No zoom, native resolution)
# This is the default, where no scaling is applied.
# xrandr --output HDMI-1 --mode 3840x2160 --scale 1x1

# 2x Scaling (for 4K displays to look like 1080p)
# This scales everything by 2x, making UI elements bigger (useful on high-DPI displays).
# This makes a 3840x2160 (4K) display behave like 1920x1080 in terms of UI size.
xrandr --output HDMI-1 --mode 3840x2160 --scale 0.5x0.5

# 3x Scaling (makes UI elements even larger)
# This would make the screen behave like a resolution close to 1280x720 (3x zoom).
xrandr --output HDMI-1 --mode 3840x2160 --scale 0.33x0.33

# Note: The lower the scale factor, the larger the UI elements appear. Adjust based on preference.

# ---- DUAL MONITORS (OPTIONAL) ----
# If you are using multiple monitors, you can position them relative to each other.
# Example: Position a second monitor (DP-1) to the right of your main HDMI-1 monitor:
# xrandr --output HDMI-1 --mode 3840x2160 --scale 0.5x0.5 --primary --output DP-1 --mode 1920x1080 --right-of HDMI-1

# ---- KEYBOARD LAYOUT (OPTIONAL) ----
# To set the keyboard layout, use the `setxkbmap` command.
# You can list available keyboard layouts using: localectl list-keymaps
# Replace "us" with your preferred layout (e.g., "de" for German, "fr" for French, "es" for Spanish)
setxkbmap us  # Set the keyboard layout to US English

# ---- AUTOSTART PROGRAMS ----
# You can autostart programs by adding them before the window manager starts.
# Make sure to add an ampersand (&) after each program to run them in the background.

# Example: Start the network manager applet in the background
nm-applet &

# Example: Set your wallpaper using `feh` (replace with your image path)
feh --bg-scale /path/to/your/wallpaper.jpg &

# Example: Start a compositor like picom (for transparency and shadow effects)
# You can install picom with: sudo pacman -S picom
picom &

# ---- START YOUR WINDOW MANAGER ----
# This is the last command in the file, and it starts your window manager.
# It must be the last line because X will terminate once this command finishes.
# Only one window manager should be started here.

# Example for dwm (Dynamic Window Manager):
exec dwm

# Example for i3 (Tiling Window Manager):
# exec i3

# Example for Openbox (Stacking Window Manager):
# exec openbox-session

# Example for xfce4 (A lightweight desktop environment):
# exec startxfce4
```
